It induces a trance-like state while providing pain relief, sedation, and memory loss.
Other uses include for chronic pain, sedation in intensive care, and depression.
Effects typically begin within five minutes when given by injection, and last up to about 25 minutes.
Ketamine is an NMDA receptor antagonist, but it may also have other actions.
It was extensively used for surgical anesthesia in the Vietnam War due to its safety.
It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines, the most effective and safe medicines needed in a health system.
It is available as a generic medication.
Ketamine is also used as a recreational drug for its hallucinogenic and dissociative effects.